<tr>
  <td class="diff-marker">&#160;</td>
  <td class="diff-context"><div>In the wake of Nur ad-Din's death, Saladin faced a difficult decision; he could move his army against the Crusaders from Egypt or wait until invited by as-Salih in Syria to come to his aid and launch a war from there. He could also take it upon himself to annex Syria before it could possibly fall into the hands of a rival, but feared that attacking a land that formerly belonged to his master—which is forbidden in the Islamic principles he followed—could portray him as hypocritical and thus, unsuitable for leading the war against the Crusaders. Saladin saw that in order to acquire Syria, he either needed an invitation from as-Salih or warn him that potential anarchy could rise danger from the Crusaders.&lt;ref&gt;{{Harvnb|Lyons|Jackson|1982|pp=74–75}}&lt;/ref&gt;</div></td>
  <td class="diff-marker">&#160;</td>
  <td class="diff-context"><div>In the wake of Nur ad-Din's death, Saladin faced a difficult decision; he could move his army against the Crusaders from Egypt or wait until invited by as-Salih in Syria to come to his aid and launch a war from there. He could also take it upon himself to annex Syria before it could possibly fall into the hands of a rival, but feared that attacking a land that formerly belonged to his master—which is forbidden in the Islamic principles he followed—could portray him as hypocritical and thus, unsuitable for leading the war against the Crusaders. Saladin saw that in order to acquire Syria, he either needed an invitation from as-Salih or warn him that potential anarchy could rise danger from the Crusaders.&lt;ref&gt;{{Harvnb|Lyons|Jackson|1982|pp=74–75}}&lt;/ref&gt;</div></td>
